    description: "Varanasi, the spiritual capital of India, is an experience that transcends ordinary tourism. Our 2-day itinerary captures the essence of Kashi — from the mystical sunrise boat ride on the Ganges to the powerful Ganga Aarti ceremony, from the ancient temples to the Buddhist site of Sarnath where Lord Buddha first taught.\n\nDay 1 immerses you in the spiritual heart of Varanasi — the ghats, temples, and the unforgettable evening Ganga Aarti at Dashashwamedh Ghat. Day 2 takes you to Sarnath, one of Buddhism's holiest sites, and then to the cultural gems of BHU and the historic Ramnagar Fort.\n\nA private cab in Varanasi is essential because the city's old quarters have narrow lanes where only walking is possible. Your driver will drop you at the closest access point to each ghat and wait while you explore on foot. For the Sarnath excursion (10 km from the city), the cab provides comfortable transport.",
    faqs: [
      { question: "Is 2 days enough for Varanasi?", answer: "Yes, 2 days covers Varanasi's highlights — sunrise boat ride, Kashi Vishwanath Temple, Ganga Aarti, Sarnath, and the ghats. Add a 3rd day for a deeper experience including Ramnagar and Chunar Fort." },
      { question: "What time is the Ganga Aarti?", answer: "The famous Ganga Aarti at Dashashwamedh Ghat starts at 6:45 PM in winter and 7:00 PM in summer. Arrive 30-45 minutes early for good viewing spots. The ceremony lasts about 45 minutes." },
      { question: "Do I need a cab in Varanasi?", answer: "Yes! While the ghats are explored on foot, you need a cab for Sarnath (10 km), Ramnagar Fort (14 km), BHU, and transfers from hotel/station. Auto-rickshaws are unreliable and expensive for tourists." },
      { question: "What is the best time to visit Varanasi?", answer: "October to March for pleasant weather. Dev Deepawali (November) is spectacular with millions of diyas on the ghats. Maha Shivaratri (Feb/March) is the biggest festival at Kashi Vishwanath." },
      { question: "Is the sunrise boat ride worth it?", answer: "Absolutely! The sunrise boat ride is the quintessential Varanasi experience. Watching the city come alive from the river — morning prayers, rituals, and the golden light on the ghats — is unforgettable." },
      { question: "How do I reach Varanasi?", answer: "Varanasi has Lal Bahadur Shastri Airport (VNS) with flights from Delhi, Mumbai, and other cities. Varanasi Junction railway station connects to all major cities. We provide pickup from both." }
    ]
